Merging the datasets so that we can have confirmed, deaths and recovered in one DataFrame¶

In [7]:
dates = confirmed_df.columns[4:]
confirmed_df_long = confirmed_df.melt(                           #Use the melt() function to un-pivot the database.
    id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'], # convert the wide format to a long format data.
    value_vars=dates, 
    var_name='Date', 
    value_name='Confirmed'
)
deaths_df_long = deaths_df.melt(
    id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'], 
    value_vars=dates, 
    var_name='Date', 
    value_name='Deaths'
)
recovered_df_long = recovered_df.melt(
    id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'], 
    value_vars=dates, 
    var_name='Date', 
    value_name='Recovered'
)

Now we might want to do something similar to what most databases including Worldometers and the amazing Indian database covid19india.org does. It is to add new columns such as New cases, New deaths, and New recovered to the above database. For that, we would have to deduct the corresponding accumulative data on the previous day.

The suggestion to do this came from one of the developers involved in the Covid19India.org database named Priya Jaiswal. Kudos to her¶

In [39]:
# new cases 

temp = full_grouped.groupby(['Country/Region', 'Date', ])['Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered']
temp = temp.sum().diff().reset_index()
mask = temp['Country/Region'] != temp['Country/Region'].shift(1)
temp.loc[mask, 'Confirmed'] = np.nan
temp.loc[mask, 'Deaths'] = np.nan
temp.loc[mask, 'Recovered'] = np.nan
# renaming columns
temp.columns = ['Country/Region', 'Date', 'New cases', 'New deaths', 'New recovered']
# merging new values
full_grouped = pd.merge(full_grouped, temp, on=['Country/Region', 'Date'])
# filling na with 0
full_grouped = full_grouped.fillna(0)
# fixing data types
cols = ['New cases', 'New deaths', 'New recovered']
full_grouped[cols] = full_grouped[cols].astype('int')
# 
full_grouped['New cases'] = full_grouped['New cases'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x<0 else x)

We analyse the spread trends by the so-called fancy Altair visualization. The size of the circle in time will show the number of cases and how big the cluster has grown as it evolves in time for the different countries.

Let's create circle chart for the daily New cases

In [107]:
alt.Chart(selected_countries).mark_circle().encode(
    x='monthdate(Date):O',
    y='Country/Region',
    color='Country/Region',
    size=alt.Size('New cases:Q',
        scale=alt.Scale(range=[0, 5000]),
        legend=alt.Legend(title='Daily new cases')
    ) 
).properties(
    width=800,
    height=300
) # taking the selected_countries as given in the row.
